@iSazonov This is more of a unacceptable changes in public contract. Quoted from the [breaking-chagne-doc](https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/blob/master/docs/dev-process/breaking-change-contract.md#unacceptable-changes):

> A code change that results in a change to the existing behavior observed for a given input with an API, protocol or the PowerShell language.

That being said, I do like the refactoring changes in `CommandSearcher.cs` and inclined to keep it.

Referencing to the algorithm and tests in https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/pull/7399#discussion_r232455452

I updated the test cases as follows:
```
@(
    @{input = '['; IsPattern = $false}
    @{input = '[]'; IsPattern = $false}
    @{input = ']['; IsPattern = $false}
    @{input = '][]'; IsPattern = $false}
    @{input = '[[]'; IsPattern = $true}
    @{input = '[]]'; IsPattern = $true}
    @{input = '[][]'; IsPattern = $true}
    @{input = ']abc'; IsPattern = $false}
    @{input = '[]abc'; IsPattern = $false}
    @{input = '[abc[]abc]'; IsPattern = $true}

    ## new test cases starting from here
    @{input = '[a-mt]ook'; IsPattern = $true}
    @{input = '[ab-z]ook'; IsPattern = $true}
    @{input = '[a?b]'; IsPattern = $true}
    @{input = '[a*]x'; IsPattern = $true}
    @{input = 'goose]'; IsPattern = $false}
    @{input = '[az-]'; IsPattern = $true}
    @{input = '[!--]a'; IsPattern = $true}
    @{input = '[e--]a'; IsPattern = $false}
    @{input = '[az-b]'; IsPattern = $false}
) | % {
    $out = if ($(ContainsValidWildcardPattern $_.input) -ne $_.IsPattern) {
        @{code = 31; verb = if ($_.IsPattern) { 'should be' } else { 'should not be' }}
    } else {
        @{code = 32; verb = if ($_.IsPattern) { 'is' } else { 'is not' }}
    }
    "`e[$($out.code)m'$($_.input)' $($out.verb) wildcard pattern`e[0m"
}
```
And this is how the current algorithm works with those test cases:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/127450/56232188-054d5c80-6035-11e9-95a0-09dc6b6fca9b.png)

It's not perfect, but is a good start. I will submit a separate PR to improve the algorithm.
@kwkam please take a look at the new test cases to make sure they are correct.

--------------------------------------

As for the refactoring changes in `CommandDiscovery.cs`, @TravisEz13's PR #9202 has been merged, which refactored this file a lot. So the refactoring changes in this PR is not relevant anymore and can be reverted now.
I will clean up this PR today.
